  <page>
    <title>Government of Barbados</title>
    <id>3514</id>
    <revision>
      <id>424328013</id>
      <timestamp>2011-04-16T07:03:13Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>131.104.246.1</ip>
      </contributor>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Government of Barbados''' consists of: [[Monarchy of Barbados|The Monarch]], HM [[Queen Elizabeth II]] (and her representative the [[Governor General of Barbados|Governor-General]], HE Sir [[Clifford Husbands]]); The Prime Minister, [[The Hon.]] [[Freundel Stuart]], and his [[Cabinet of Barbados|Cabinet]]; ([[Parliament of Barbados|Parliament]]) as legislature, divided into two chambers ([[Senate of Barbados|Senate]] and [[Barbados House of Assembly|House of Assembly]]), and an independent judiciary. In keeping with the evolution of the [[Westminster system]] of governance, Barbados has evolved into a [[Parliamentary democracy]] and [[Constitutional monarchy]], meaning that all [[Political power|real power]] rests with the Parliament.
Executive authority is vested in both the Prime Minister and Cabinet who are collectively responsible to Parliament. Barbadian law is rooted historically on [[English law|English common law]], and the [[Constitution of Barbados]] implemented in 1966, is supreme [[law of the land]].

==History==
The government has been chosen by elections since [[Barbadian general election, 1961|1961 elections]], when Barbados achieved full [[Self-governing colony|self-governance]].  Before then, the government was a [[Crown colony]] consisting of either colonial administration solely (such as the [[Executive Council (Commonwealth countries)|Executive Council]]), or a mixture of colonial rule and a partially-elected assembly, such as the [[Legislative Council of Barbados|Legislative Council]].  Both the [[Barbados Labour Party]] and the [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] have formed the government in the elections since 1961.

== Executive Branch ==
The Prime Minister and Cabinet is formed by the [[political party]] which gains a simple majority in the [[Elections in Barbados|general election]]s held in [[Barbados]].  These elections constitutionally must be held no longer than every five years apart, however elections can be called whenever the Government so chooses to seek a new mandate or loses a vote of [[no confidence]] in [[Parliament of Barbados|Parliament]].  It is part of [[Politics of Barbados|Barbados' political system]] and supported by the [[Barbadian Public Service|Public service]].

