      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Politics of Brazil}}
'''Politics of Brazil''' takes place in a framework of a [[federation|federal]] [[presidential system|presidential]] [[representative democracy|representative democratic]] [[republic]], whereby the [[President of Brazil]] is both [[head of state]] and [[head of government]], and of a [[multi-party system]]. [[Executive power]] is exercised by the government. [[Legislative power]] is vested in both the [[government]] and the two chambers of the [[National Congress of Brazil|National Congress]]. The [[Judiciary]] is independent of the executive and the legislature. [[Brazil]] is divided into 26 [[state (administrative division)|state]]s, one [[Brazilian Federal District|Federal District]] and over 5,500 [[municipality|municipalities]].

==Government of Brazil==
[[File:Senado2006.jpg|thumb|Brazilian senate.]]

The [[Constitution of Brazil|1988 constitution]] grants broad powers to the federal government, made up of [[Executive (government)|Executive]], [[Legislative]], and [[Judiciary|Judicial]] branches. The [[President of Brazil|President]] holds office for four years, with the right to re-election for an additional four-year term, and appoints his or her own cabinet.

===Executive branch===
{{See|Cabinet of Brazil}}
{{office-table}}
