      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}
'''Transport''' infrastructure '''in [[Brazil]]''' is characterized by strong regional differences and lack of development of the national rail network.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.dhl-discoverlogistics.com/cms/en/course/trends/america/brazil.jsp&lt;/ref&gt; Brazil's fast growing economy, and especially the growth in exports, will place increasing demands on the transport networks.&lt;ref name=&quot;ic.gc.ca&quot;&gt;http://www.ic.gc.ca/scdt/bizmap/interface2.nsf/vDownload/ISA_3976/$file/X_9317614.PDF&lt;/ref&gt; However, sizeable new investments that are expected to address some of the issues are either planned or in progress.&lt;ref name=&quot;ic.gc.ca&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;http://www.bsdlive.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=3130466&lt;/ref&gt;

== [[Rail transport|Railways]] ==
''{{Main|Rail transport in Brazil}}''
{{See|RFFSA}}
[[Image:Linha A1700CPTM.jpg|thumb|Urban/suburban rail in [[São Paulo]]]]
*'''Total actual network:''' 29,295&amp;nbsp;km
:[[Broad gauge]]: 4,932 km {{RailGauge|1.6}} gauge (939 km electrified)
:[[Narrow gauge railway|Narrow gauge]]: 23,773 km {{RailGauge|1}} gauge (581 km electrified)
:[[Dual gauge]]: 396 km 1000 mm and 1600 mm gauges (three rails)
:[[Standard gauge]]: 194 km {{RailGauge|sg}} gauge: (2006)

&lt;!--* line 5 of the [[São Paulo Metro]], so that it can use &quot;[[off the shelf]]&quot; equipment.--&gt;
* [[Estrada de Ferro do Amapá]] in the middle of the [[Amazon Rainforest]] also used standard gauge.
* A 12&amp;nbsp;km section of the former {{RailGauge|30}} gauge [[Estrada de Ferro Oeste de Minas]] is retained as a [[heritage railway]].

